<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="367" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/1764¾</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-20">
                                    <hi rend="italic">20 May, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: As I intimated in the
                            little scribbled note I sent back by the special messenger whom you sent
                            with this to New York, I think your position in the conversation with
                            the Austrian Ambassador was admirable. We clearly cannot afford to
                            consult with Germany as to our course toward Great Britain. The two must
                            be kept carefully separate and distinct.</p>
                        <p>I am glad to be back and at my desk.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>